# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: real-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] In mathematics, a function f defined on some set X with real or complex values is called **bounded** if the set of its values (its image) is bounded.
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] A function that is *not* bounded is said to be **unbounded**.
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] If f is real-valued and $f(x)\leq A$ for all x in X , then the function is said to be **bounded (from) above** by A .
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] If $f(x)\geq B$ for all x in X , then the function is said to be **bounded (from) below** by B .
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] A real-valued function is bounded if and only if it is bounded from above and below.
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] An important special case is a **bounded sequence**, where *X* is taken to be the set $\mathbb {N}$ of natural numbers.
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] The set of all bounded sequences forms the sequence space $l^{\infty }$ .
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] The definition of boundedness can be generalized to functions $f:X\rightarrow Y$ taking values in a more general space Y by requiring that the image $f(X)$ is a bounded set in Y .
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] Weaker than boundedness is local boundedness.
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] A family of bounded functions may be uniformly bounded.
[src:real-analysis/bounded-function] Boundedness can also be determined by looking at a graph.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] of the sequence do not get arbitrarily close to each other as the sequence progresses.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] In mathematics, a **Cauchy sequence** is a sequence whose elements become arbitrarily close to each other as the sequence progresses.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] More precisely, given any small positive distance, all excluding a finite number of elements of the sequence are less than that given distance from each other.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Cauchy sequences are named after Augustin-Louis Cauchy; they may occasionally be known as **fundamental sequences**.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] It is not sufficient for each term to become arbitrarily close to the *preceding* term.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] However, with growing values of n, the terms $a_{n}$ become arbitrarily large.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] So, for any index n and distance d, there exists an index m big enough such that $a_{m}-a_{n}>d.$ As a result, no matter how far one goes, the remaining terms of the sequence never get close to *each other*; hence the sequence is not Cauchy.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] This is often exploited in algorithms, both theoretical and applied, where an iterative process can be shown relatively easily to produce a Cauchy sequence, consisting of the iterates, thus fulfilling a logical condition, such as termination.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Generalizations of Cauchy sequences in more abstract uniform spaces exist in the form of Cauchy filters and Cauchy nets.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] A sequence $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\ldots$ of real numbers is called a Cauchy sequence if for every positive real number $\varepsilon ,$ there is a positive integer *N* such that for all natural numbers $m,n>N,$ $|x_{m}-x_{n}|<\varepsilon ,$ where the vertical bars denote the absolute value.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] In a similar way one can define Cauchy sequences of rational or complex numbers.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Cauchy formulated such a condition by requiring $x_{m}-x_{n}$ to be infinitesimal for every pair of infinite *m*, *n*.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] For any real number *r*, the sequence of truncated decimal expansions of *r* forms a Cauchy sequence.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Any sequence with a modulus of Cauchy convergence is a Cauchy sequence.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] The existence of a modulus for a Cauchy sequence follows from the well-ordering property of the natural numbers (let $\alpha (k)$ be the smallest possible N in the definition of Cauchy sequence, taking $\varepsilon$ to be $1/k$ ).
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] The existence of a modulus also follows from the principle of countable choice.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] *Regular Cauchy sequences* are sequences with a given modulus of Cauchy convergence (usually $\alpha (k)=k$ or $\alpha (k)=2^{k}$ ).
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Any Cauchy sequence with a modulus of Cauchy convergence is equivalent to a regular Cauchy sequence; this can be proven without using any form of the axiom of choice.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Moduli of Cauchy convergence are used by constructive mathematicians who do not wish to use any form of choice.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Using a modulus of Cauchy convergence can simplify both definitions and theorems in constructive analysis.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Regular Cauchy sequences were used by Bishop (2012) and by Bridges (1997) in constructive mathematics textbooks.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Since the definition of a Cauchy sequence only involves metric concepts, it is straightforward to generalize it to any metric space *X*.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Roughly speaking, the terms of the sequence are getting closer and closer together in a way that suggests that the sequence ought to have a limit in *X*.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Nonetheless, such a limit does not always exist within *X*: the property of a space that every Cauchy sequence converges in the space is called *completeness*, and is detailed below.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] A metric space (*X*, *d*) in which every Cauchy sequence converges to an element of *X* is called complete.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] For any metric space *M*, it is possible to construct a complete metric space *M′* that contains *M* as a dense subspace; see Complete metric space § Completion.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] The real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ are complete under the metric induced by the usual absolute value, and one of the standard constructions of the real numbers involves Cauchy sequences of rational numbers.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] In this construction, each equivalence class of Cauchy sequences of rational numbers with a certain tail behavior—that is, each class of sequences that get arbitrarily close to one another— is a real number.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] A rather different type of example is afforded by a metric space *X* which has the discrete metric (where any two distinct points are at distance 1 from each other).
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Any Cauchy sequence of elements of *X* must be constant beyond some fixed point, and converges to the eventually repeating term.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] These last two properties, together with the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem, yield one standard proof of the completeness of the real numbers, closely related to both the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem and the Heine–Borel theorem.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Every Cauchy sequence of real numbers is bounded, hence by Bolzano–Weierstrass has a convergent subsequence, hence is itself convergent.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] This proof of the completeness of the real numbers implicitly makes use of the least upper bound axiom.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] The alternative approach, mentioned above, of *constructing* the real numbers as the completion of the rational numbers, makes the completeness of the real numbers tautological.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] One of the standard illustrations of the advantage of being able to work with Cauchy sequences and make use of completeness is provided by consideration of the summation of an infinite series of real numbers (or, more generally, of elements of any complete normed linear space, or Banach space).
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] If $f:M\to N$ is a uniformly continuous map between the metric spaces *M* and *N* and (*x**n*) is a Cauchy sequence in *M*, then $(f(x_{n}))$ is a Cauchy sequence in *N*.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] If $(x_{n})$ and $(y_{n})$ are two Cauchy sequences in the rational, real or complex numbers, then the sum $(x_{n}+y_{n})$ and the product $(x_{n}y_{n})$ are also Cauchy sequences.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] It is symmetric since $y_{n}x_{m}^{-1}=(x_{m}y_{n}^{-1})^{-1}\in U^{-1}$ which by continuity of the inverse is another open neighbourhood of the identity.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] It is transitive since $x_{n}z_{l}^{-1}=x_{n}y_{m}^{-1}y_{m}z_{l}^{-1}\in U'U''$ where $U'$ and $U''$ are open neighbourhoods of the identity such that $U'U''\subseteq U$ ; such pairs exist by the continuity of the group operation.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] There is also a concept of Cauchy sequence in a group G : Let $H=(H_{r})$ be a decreasing sequence of normal subgroups of G of finite index.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Technically, this is the same thing as a topological group Cauchy sequence for a particular choice of topology on $G,$ namely that for which H is a local base.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] If H is a cofinal sequence (that is, any normal subgroup of finite index contains some $H_{r}$ ), then this completion is canonical in the sense that it is isomorphic to the inverse limit of $(G/H)_{H},$ where H varies over *all* normal subgroups of finite index.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] A real sequence $\langle u_{n}:n\in \mathbb {N} \rangle$ has a natural hyperreal extension, defined for hypernatural values *H* of the index *n* in addition to the usual natural *n*.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] where "st" is the standard part function.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Krause (2020) introduced a notion of Cauchy completion of a category.
[src:real-analysis/cauchy-sequence] Applied to $\mathbb {Q}$ (the category whose objects are rational numbers, and there is a morphism from *x* to *y* if and only if $x\leq y$ ), this Cauchy completion yields $\mathbb {R} \cup \left\{\infty \right\}$ (again interpreted as a category using its natural ordering).
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] As the positive integer ${\textstyle n}$ becomes larger and larger, the value ${\textstyle n\times \sin \left({\tfrac {1}{n}}\right)}$ becomes arbitrarily close to ${\textstyle 1}$ .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In mathematics, the **limit of a sequence** is the value that the terms of a sequence "tend to", and is often denoted using the $\lim$ symbol (e.g., $\lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}$ ).
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] If such a limit exists and is finite, the sequence is called **convergent**.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] A sequence that does not converge is said to be **divergent**.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The limit of a sequence is said to be the fundamental notion on which the whole of mathematical analysis ultimately rests.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] Limits can be defined in any metric or topological space, but are usually first encountered in the real numbers.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The Greek philosopher Zeno of Elea is famous for formulating paradoxes that involve limiting processes.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] Leucippus, Democritus, Antiphon, Eudoxus, and Archimedes developed the method of exhaustion, which uses an infinite sequence of approximations to determine an area or a volume.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] Archimedes succeeded in summing what is now called a geometric series in his *Quadrature of the Parabola*, computing the area enclosed by a parabola and a straight line.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] Pietro Mengoli anticipated the modern idea of limit of a sequence with his study of quasi-proportions in *Geometriae speciosae elementa* (1659).
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] He used the term *quasi-infinite* for unbounded and *quasi-null* for vanishing.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In the latter work, Newton considers the binomial expansion of ${\textstyle (x+o)^{n}}$ , which he then linearizes by *taking the limit* as ${\textstyle o}$ tends to ${\textstyle 0}$ .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In the 18th century, mathematicians such as Euler succeeded in summing some *divergent* series by stopping at the right moment; they did not much care whether a limit existed, as long as it could be calculated.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] At the end of the century, Lagrange in his *Théorie des fonctions analytiques* (1797) opined that the lack of rigour precluded further development in calculus.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] Gauss in his study of hypergeometric series (1813) for the first time rigorously investigated the conditions under which a series converged to a limit.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The modern definition of a limit (for any ${\textstyle \varepsilon }$ there exists an index ${\textstyle N}$ so that ...) was given by Bernard Bolzano (*Der binomische Lehrsatz*, Prague 1816, which was little noticed at the time), and by Karl Weierstrass in the 1870s.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In the real numbers, a number L is the limit of the sequence $(x_{n})$ , if the numbers in the sequence become closer and closer to L , and not to any other number.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In other words, for every measure of closeness $\varepsilon$ , the sequence's terms are eventually that close to the limit.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The sequence $(x_{n})$ is said to **converge to** or **tend to** the limit x .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] If a sequence $(x_{n})$ converges to some limit x , then it is **convergent** and x is the only limit; otherwise $(x_{n})$ is **divergent**.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] A sequence that has zero as its limit is sometimes called a **null sequence**.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] These properties are extensively used to prove limits, without the need to directly use the cumbersome formal definition.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] For example, once it is proven that $1/n\to 0$ , it becomes easy to show—using the properties above—that ${\frac {a}{b+{\frac {c}{n}}}}\to {\frac {a}{b}}$ (assuming that $b\neq 0$ ).
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] If a sequence tends to infinity or minus infinity, then it is divergent.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] However, a divergent sequence need not tend to plus or minus infinity, and the sequence $x_{n}=(-1)^{n}$ provides one such example.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] This coincides with the definition given for real numbers when $X=\mathbb {R}$ and $d(x,y)=|x-y|$ .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] A Cauchy sequence is a sequence whose terms ultimately become arbitrarily close together, after sufficiently many initial terms have been discarded.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The notion of a Cauchy sequence is important in the study of sequences in metric spaces, and, in particular, in real analysis.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] One particularly important result in real analysis is the *Cauchy criterion for convergence of sequences*: a sequence of real numbers is convergent if and only if it is a Cauchy sequence.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] This remains true in other complete metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] This coincides with the definition given for metric spaces, if $(X,d)$ is a metric space and $\tau$ is the topology generated by d .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In a Hausdorff space, limits of sequences are unique whenever they exist.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] This need not be the case in non-Hausdorff spaces; in particular, if two points x and y are topologically indistinguishable, then any sequence that converges to x must converge to y and vice versa.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The definition of the limit using the hyperreal numbers formalizes the intuition that for a "very large" value of the index, the corresponding term is "very close" to the limit.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] More precisely, a real sequence $(x_{n})$ tends to *L* if for every infinite hypernatural ${\textstyle H}$ , the term $x_{H}$ is infinitely close to ${\textstyle L}$ (i.e., the difference $x_{H}-L$ is infinitesimal).
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] where the limit exists if and only if the righthand side is independent of the choice of an infinite *${\textstyle H}$*.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] Sometimes one may also consider a sequence with more than one index, for example, a double sequence $(x_{n,m})$ .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] This sequence has a limit L if it becomes closer and closer to L when both *n* and *m* becomes very large.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The sequence $(x_{n,m})$ is said to **converge to** or **tend to** the limit x .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] The double limit is different from taking limit in *n* first, and then in *m*.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] Given that both the double limit and the iterated limit exists, they have the same value.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] However, it is possible that one of them exist but the other does not.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] However, a divergent sequence need not tend to plus or minus infinity, and the sequence $x_{n,m}=(-1)^{n+m}$ provides one such example.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] For a double sequence $(x_{n,m})$ , we may take limit in one of the indices, say, $n\to \infty$ , to obtain a single sequence $(y_{m})$ .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In fact, there are two possible meanings when taking this limit.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] When such a limit exists, we say the sequence $(x_{n,m})$ converges pointwise to $(y_{m})$ .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In this definition, the choice of N is independent of m .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] In other words, the choice of N is *uniformly applicable* to all natural numbers m .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] When such a limit exists, we say the sequence $(x_{n,m})$ converges uniformly to $(y_{m})$ .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] For a double sequence $(x_{n,m})$ , we may take limit in one of the indices, say, $n\to \infty$ , to obtain a single sequence $(y_{m})$ , and then take limit in the other index, namely $m\to \infty$ , to get a number y .
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] This limit is known as **iterated limit** of the double sequence.
[src:real-analysis/limit-of-a-sequence] A sufficient condition of equality is given by the Moore-Osgood theorem, which requires the limit $\lim _{n\to \infty }x_{n,m}=y_{m}$ to be uniform in ${\textstyle m}$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In mathematics, a **metric space** is a set together with a notion of distance between its points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The distance is measured by a function called a **metric** or **distance function**.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Metric spaces are a general setting for studying many of the concepts of mathematical analysis and geometry.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The most familiar example of a metric space is 3-dimensional Euclidean space with its usual notion of distance.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Other well-known examples are a sphere equipped with the angular distance and the hyperbolic plane.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A metric may correspond to a metaphorical, rather than physical, notion of distance.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, the set of 100-character Unicode strings can be equipped with the Hamming distance, which measures the number of characters that need to be changed to get from one string to another.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Metric spaces appear in many different branches of mathematics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, Riemannian manifolds, normed vector spaces, and graphs may be viewed as metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In abstract algebra, the field of *p*-adic numbers is the completion of the field of rational numbers with respect to a certain metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Metric spaces are also studied in their own right in **metric geometry** and **analysis on metric spaces**.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Many notions of analysis, including balls, completeness, as well as uniform, Lipschitz, and Hölder continuity can be defined for metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Other notions, such as continuity, compactness, and open and closed sets can be defined for metric spaces, but also in the even more general setting of topological spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] To see the utility of different notions of distance, consider the surface of the Earth as a set of points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] We can measure the distance between two such points by the length of the shortest path along the surface, "as the crow flies"; this is particularly useful for shipping and aviation.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] We can also measure the straight-line distance between two points through the Earth's interior; this notion is, for example, natural in seismology, since it roughly corresponds to the length of time it takes for seismic waves to travel between those two points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The notion of distance encoded by the metric space axioms has relatively few requirements.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This generality gives metric spaces a lot of flexibility.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] At the same time, the notion is strong enough to encode many intuitive facts about what distance means.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This means that general results about metric spaces can be applied in many different contexts.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Like many fundamental mathematical concepts, the metric on a metric space can be interpreted in many different ways.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The triangle inequality holds: $d(x,z)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,z)$ This is a natural property of both physical and metaphorical notions of distance: you can arrive at z from x by taking a detour through y, but this will not make your journey any shorter than the direct path.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] It is traditional to write M as an abbreviation for (*M*, *d*) when it is understood what d is.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The real numbers with the distance function $d(x,y)=|y-x|$ given by the absolute difference form a metric space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Many properties of metric spaces and functions between them are generalizations of concepts in real analysis and coincide with those concepts when applied to the real line.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The Euclidean plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ can be equipped with many different metrics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The *taxicab* or *Manhattan* distance is defined by $d_{1}((x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}))=|x_{2}-x_{1}|+|y_{2}-y_{1}|$ and can be thought of as the distance you need to travel along horizontal and vertical lines to get from one point to the other, as illustrated at the top of the article.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The *maximum*, $L^{\infty }$ , or *Chebyshev distance* is defined by $d_{\infty }((x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}))=\max\{|x_{2}-x_{1}|,|y_{2}-y_{1}|\}.$ This distance does not have an easy explanation in terms of paths in the plane, but it still satisfies the metric space axioms.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] It can be thought of similarly to the number of moves a king would have to make on a chess board to travel from one point to another on the given space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In fact, these three distances, while they have distinct properties, are similar in some ways.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Informally, points that are close in one are close in the others, too.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This observation can be quantified with the formula $d_{\infty }(p,q)\leq d_{2}(p,q)\leq d_{1}(p,q)\leq 2d_{\infty }(p,q),$ which holds for every pair of points $p,q\in \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Moreover, there exists a continuous family of distances $d_{\alpha }$ for $\alpha \in (1,\infty )$ that interpolates between these three distances.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A radically different distance can be defined by setting $d(p,q)={\begin{cases}0,&{\text{if }}p=q,\\1,&{\text{otherwise.}}\end{cases}}$ In this *discrete metric*, all distinct points are 1 unit apart: none of them are close to each other, and none of them are very far away from each other either.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Intuitively, the discrete metric no longer remembers that the set is a plane, but treats it just as an undifferentiated set of points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] All of these metrics can be easily extended to make sense on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as well as $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Given a metric space (*M*, *d*) and a subset $A\subseteq M$ , we can consider A to be a metric space by measuring distances the same way we would in M.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Two more useful examples are the open interval (0, 1) and the closed interval [0, 1] thought of as subspaces of the real line.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Arthur Cayley, in his article "On Distance", extended metric concepts beyond Euclidean geometry into domains bounded by a conic in a projective space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] His distance was given by logarithm of a cross ratio.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Any projectivity leaving the conic stable also leaves the cross ratio constant, so isometries are implicit.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This method provides models for elliptic geometry and hyperbolic geometry, and Felix Klein, in several publications, established the field of non-euclidean geometry through the use of the Cayley-Klein metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The idea of an abstract space with metric properties was addressed in 1906 by René Maurice Fréchet and the term *metric space* was coined by Felix Hausdorff in 1914.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Fréchet's work laid the foundation for understanding convergence, continuity, and other key concepts in non-geometric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This allowed mathematicians to study functions and sequences in a broader and more flexible way.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This was important for the growing field of functional analysis.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Mathematicians like Hausdorff and Stefan Banach further refined and expanded the framework of metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Hausdorff introduced topological spaces as a generalization of metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Banach's work in functional analysis heavily relied on the metric structure.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Over time, metric spaces became a central part of modern mathematics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] They have influenced various fields including topology, geometry, and applied mathematics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Metric spaces continue to play a crucial role in the study of abstract mathematical concepts.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A distance function is enough to define notions of closeness and convergence that were first developed in real analysis.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Properties that depend on the structure of a metric space are referred to as *metric properties*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Every metric space is also a topological space, and some metric properties can also be rephrased without reference to distance in the language of topology; that is, they are really topological properties.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For any point x in a metric space M and any real number *r* > 0, the *open ball* of radius r around x is defined to be the set of points that are strictly less than distance r from x: $B_{r}(x)=\{y\in M:d(x,y)<r\}.$ This is a natural way to define a set of points that are relatively close to x.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Therefore, a set $N\subseteq M$ is a *neighborhood* of x (informally, it contains all points "close enough" to x) if it contains an open ball of radius r around x for some *r* > 0.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] An *open set* is a set which is a neighborhood of all its points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] It follows that the open balls form a base for a topology on M.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In other words, the open sets of M are exactly the unions of open balls.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] As in any topology, closed sets are the complements of open sets.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Sets may be both open and closed as well as neither open nor closed.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This topology does not carry all the information about the metric space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, the distances *d*1, *d*2, and *d*∞ defined above all induce the same topology on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , although they behave differently in many respects.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Similarly, $\mathbb {R}$ with the Euclidean metric and its subspace the interval (0, 1) with the induced metric are homeomorphic but have very different metric properties.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Conversely, not every topological space can be given a metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Topological spaces which are compatible with a metric are called *metrizable* and are particularly well-behaved in many ways: in particular, they are paracompact Hausdorff spaces (hence normal) and first-countable.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The Nagata–Smirnov metrization theorem gives a characterization of metrizability in terms of other topological properties, without reference to metrics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In metric spaces, both of these definitions make sense and they are equivalent.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This is a general pattern for topological properties of metric spaces: while they can be defined in a purely topological way, there is often a way that uses the metric which is easier to state or more familiar from real analysis.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Informally, a metric space is *complete* if it has no "missing points": every sequence that looks like it should converge to something actually converges.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] To make this precise: a sequence (*xn*) in a metric space M is a Cauchy sequence if for every ε > 0 there is an integer N such that for all *m*, *n* > *N*, *d*(*xm*, *xn*) < ε.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] By the triangle inequality, any convergent sequence is a Cauchy sequence: if xm and xn are both less than ε away from the limit, then they are less than 2ε away from each other.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] If the converse is true—every Cauchy sequence in M converges—then M is complete.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Euclidean spaces are complete, as is $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ with the other metrics described above.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Two examples of spaces which are not complete are (0, 1) and the rationals, each with the metric induced from $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] One can think of (0, 1) as "missing" its endpoints 0 and 1.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The rationals are missing all the irrationals, since any irrational has a sequence of rationals converging to it in $\mathbb {R}$ (for example, its successive decimal approximations).
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] These examples show that completeness is *not* a topological property, since $\mathbb {R}$ is complete but the homeomorphic space (0, 1) is not.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This notion of "missing points" can be made precise.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In fact, every metric space has a unique *completion*, which is a complete space that contains the given space as a dense subset.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, [0, 1] is the completion of (0, 1), and the real numbers are the completion of the rationals.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Since complete spaces are generally easier to work with, completions are important throughout mathematics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, in abstract algebra, the *p*-adic numbers are defined as the completion of the rationals under a different metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Completion is particularly common as a tool in functional analysis.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Often one has a set of nice functions and a way of measuring distances between them.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Taking the completion of this metric space gives a new set of functions which may be less nice, but nevertheless useful because they behave similarly to the original nice functions in important ways.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, weak solutions to differential equations typically live in a completion (a Sobolev space) rather than the original space of nice functions for which the differential equation actually makes sense.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A metric space M is *bounded* if there is an r such that no pair of points in M is more than distance r apart.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The least such r is called the diameter of M.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The space M is called *precompact* or *totally bounded* if for every *r* > 0 there is a finite cover of M by open balls of radius r.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] To see this, start with a finite cover by r-balls for some arbitrary r.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Since the subset of M consisting of the centers of these balls is finite, it has finite diameter, say D.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] By the triangle inequality, the diameter of the whole space is at most *D* + 2*r*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The converse does not hold: an example of a metric space that is bounded but not totally bounded is $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ (or any other infinite set) with the discrete metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Compactness is a topological property which generalizes the properties of a closed and bounded subset of Euclidean space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A metric space M is compact if every sequence has a convergent subsequence.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A metric space M is compact if it is complete and totally bounded.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] One example of a compact space is the closed interval [0, 1].
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Compactness is important for similar reasons to completeness: it makes it easy to find limits.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Another important tool is Lebesgue's number lemma, which shows that for any open cover of a compact space, every point is relatively deep inside one of the sets of the cover.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Unlike in the case of topological spaces or algebraic structures such as groups or rings, there is no single "right" type of structure-preserving function between metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Instead, one works with different types of functions depending on one's goals.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The words "function" and "map" are used interchangeably.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] It follows from the metric space axioms that a distance-preserving function is injective.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A bijective distance-preserving function is called an *isometry*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] If there is an isometry between the spaces *M*1 and *M*2, they are said to be *isometric*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Metric spaces that are isometric are essentially identical.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] On the other end of the spectrum, one can forget entirely about the metric structure and study continuous maps, which only preserve topological structure.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] There are several equivalent definitions of continuity for metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A *homeomorphism* is a continuous bijection whose inverse is also continuous; if there is a homeomorphism between *M*1 and *M*2, they are said to be *homeomorphic*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Homeomorphic spaces are the same from the point of view of topology, but may have very different metric properties.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, $\mathbb {R}$ is unbounded and complete, while (0, 1) is bounded but not complete.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The only difference between this definition and the ε–δ definition of continuity is the order of quantifiers: the choice of δ must depend only on ε and not on the point x.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] However, this subtle change makes a big difference.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, uniformly continuous maps take Cauchy sequences in *M*1 to Cauchy sequences in *M*2.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In other words, uniform continuity preserves some metric properties which are not purely topological.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] On the other hand, the Heine–Cantor theorem states that if *M*1 is compact, then every continuous map is uniformly continuous.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In other words, uniform continuity cannot distinguish any non-topological features of compact metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A Lipschitz map is one that stretches distances by at most a bounded factor.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, a curve in a metric space is rectifiable (has finite length) if and only if it has a Lipschitz reparametrization.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A 1-Lipschitz map is sometimes called a *nonexpanding* or *metric map*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Metric maps are commonly taken to be the morphisms of the category of metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A K-Lipschitz map for *K* < 1 is called a *contraction*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The Banach fixed-point theorem states that if M is a complete metric space, then every contraction $f:M\to M$ admits a unique fixed point.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A quasi-isometry is a map that preserves the "large-scale structure" of a metric space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Quasi-isometries need not be continuous.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ and its subspace $\mathbb {Z} ^{2}$ are quasi-isometric, even though one is connected and the other is discrete.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The equivalence relation of quasi-isometry is important in geometric group theory: the Švarc–Milnor lemma states that all spaces on which a group acts geometrically are quasi-isometric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A normed vector space is a vector space equipped with a *norm*, which is a function that measures the length of vectors.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The norm of a vector v is typically denoted by $\lVert v\rVert$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Any normed vector space can be equipped with a metric in which the distance between two vectors x and y is given by $d(x,y):=\lVert x-y\rVert .$ The metric d is said to be *induced* by the norm $\lVert {\cdot }\rVert$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] then ${\displaystyle \lVert x\rVert$ is a norm induced by the metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A similar relationship holds between seminorms and pseudometrics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Among examples of metrics induced by a norm are the metrics *d*1, *d*2, and *d*∞ on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , which are induced by the Manhattan norm, the Euclidean norm, and the maximum norm, respectively.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] More generally, the Kuratowski embedding allows one to see any metric space as a subspace of a normed vector space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Infinite-dimensional normed vector spaces, particularly spaces of functions, are studied in functional analysis.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Completeness is particularly important in this context: a complete normed vector space is known as a Banach space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] An unusual property of normed vector spaces is that linear transformations between them are continuous if and only if they are Lipschitz.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Such transformations are known as bounded operators.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A curve in a metric space (*M*, *d*) is a continuous function ${\displaystyle \gamma$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The length of γ is measured by $L(\gamma )=\sup _{0=x_{0}<x_{1}<\cdots <x_{n}=T}\left\{\sum _{k=1}^{n}d(\gamma (x_{k-1}),\gamma (x_{k}))\right\}.$ In general, this supremum may be infinite; a curve of finite length is called *rectifiable*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Suppose that the length of the curve γ is equal to the distance between its endpoints—that is, it is the shortest possible path between its endpoints.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] After reparametrization by arc length, γ becomes a *geodesic*: a curve which is a distance-preserving function.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A geodesic is a shortest possible path between any two of its points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A *geodesic metric space* is a metric space which admits a geodesic between any two of its points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In $(\mathbb {R} ^{2},d_{2})$ , geodesics are unique, but in $(\mathbb {R} ^{2},d_{1})$ , there are often infinitely many geodesics between two points, as shown in the figure at the top of the article.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The space M is a *length space* (or the metric d is *intrinsic*) if the distance between any two points x and y is the infimum of lengths of paths between them.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Unlike in a geodesic metric space, the infimum does not have to be attained.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] An example of a length space which is not geodesic is the Euclidean plane minus the origin: the points (1, 0) and (-1, 0) can be joined by paths of length arbitrarily close to 2, but not by a path of length 2.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] An example of a metric space which is not a length space is given by the straight-line metric on the sphere: the straight line between two points through the center of the Earth is shorter than any path along the surface.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Given any metric space (*M*, *d*), one can define a new, intrinsic distance function *d*intrinsic on M by setting the distance between points x and y to be the infimum of the d-lengths of paths between them.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For instance, if d is the straight-line distance on the sphere, then *d*intrinsic is the great-circle distance.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] However, in some cases *d*intrinsic may have infinite values.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, if M is the Koch snowflake with the subspace metric d induced from $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , then the resulting intrinsic distance is infinite for any pair of distinct points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A Riemannian manifold is a space equipped with a Riemannian metric tensor, which determines lengths of tangent vectors at every point.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This can be thought of defining a notion of distance infinitesimally.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This construction generalizes to other kinds of infinitesimal metrics on manifolds, such as sub-Riemannian and Finsler metrics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The Riemannian metric is uniquely determined by the distance function; this means that in principle, all information about a Riemannian manifold can be recovered from its distance function.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] One direction in metric geometry is finding purely metric ("synthetic") formulations of properties of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, a Riemannian manifold is a CAT(*k*) space (a synthetic condition which depends purely on the metric) if and only if its sectional curvature is bounded above by k.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Thus CAT(*k*) spaces generalize upper curvature bounds to general metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Real analysis makes use of both the metric on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and the Lebesgue measure.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Therefore, generalizations of many ideas from analysis naturally reside in metric measure spaces: spaces that have both a measure and a metric which are compatible with each other.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Formally, a *metric measure space* is a metric space equipped with a Borel regular measure such that every ball has positive measure.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example Euclidean spaces of dimension n, and more generally n-dimensional Riemannian manifolds, naturally have the structure of a metric measure space, equipped with the Lebesgue measure.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Certain fractal metric spaces such as the Sierpiński gasket can be equipped with the α-dimensional Hausdorff measure where α is the Hausdorff dimension.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In general, however, a metric space may not have an "obvious" choice of measure.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] One application of metric measure spaces is generalizing the notion of Ricci curvature beyond Riemannian manifolds.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Just as CAT(*k*) and Alexandrov spaces generalize sectional curvature bounds, RCD spaces are a class of metric measure spaces which generalize lower bounds on Ricci curvature.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A metric space is *discrete* if its induced topology is the discrete topology.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Although many concepts, such as completeness and compactness, are not interesting for such spaces, they are nevertheless an object of study in several branches of mathematics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In particular, finite metric spaces (those having a finite number of points) are studied in combinatorics and theoretical computer science.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Embeddings in other metric spaces are particularly well-studied.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, not every finite metric space can be isometrically embedded in a Euclidean space or in Hilbert space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] On the other hand, in the worst case the required distortion (bilipschitz constant) is only logarithmic in the number of points.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For any undirected connected graph G, the set V of vertices of G can be turned into a metric space by defining the distance between vertices x and y to be the length of the shortest edge path connecting them.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In graph theory, this is also called the shortest-path distance or geodesic distance.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In geometric group theory this construction is applied to the Cayley graph of a (typically infinite) finitely-generated group, yielding the word metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Up to quasi-isometry, the word metric depends only on the group and not on the chosen finite generating set.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] An important area of study in finite metric spaces is the embedding of complex metric spaces into simpler ones while controlling the distortion of distances.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This is particularly useful in computer science and discrete mathematics, where algorithms often perform more efficiently on simpler structures like tree metrics.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A significant result in this area is that any finite metric space can be probabilistically embedded into a *tree metric* with an expected distortion of $O(\log n)$ , where n is the number of points in the metric space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This embedding is notable because it achieves the best possible asymptotic bound on distortion, matching the lower bound of $\Omega (\log n)$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The tree metrics produced in this embedding *dominate* the original metrics, meaning that distances in the tree are greater than or equal to those in the original space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] This property is particularly useful for designing approximation algorithms, as it allows for the preservation of distance-related properties while simplifying the underlying structure.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The technique involves constructing a hierarchical decomposition of the original metric space and converting it into a tree metric via a randomized algorithm.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The $O(\log n)$ distortion bound has led to improved approximation ratios in several algorithmic problems, demonstrating the practical significance of this theoretical result.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In modern mathematics, one often studies spaces whose points are themselves mathematical objects.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A distance function on such a space generally aims to measure the dissimilarity between two objects.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The idea of spaces of mathematical objects can also be applied to subsets of a metric space, as well as metric spaces themselves.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Hausdorff and Gromov–Hausdorff distance define metrics on the set of compact subsets of a metric space and the set of compact metric spaces, respectively.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Suppose (*M*, *d*) is a metric space, and let S be a subset of M.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The *distance from S to a point x of M* is, informally, the distance from x to the closest point of S.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] However, since there may not be a single closest point, it is defined via an infimum: $d(x,S)=\inf\{d(x,s):s\in S\}.$ In particular, $d(x,S)=0$ if and only if x belongs to the closure of S.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Furthermore, distances between points and sets satisfy a version of the triangle inequality: $d(x,S)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,S),$ and therefore the map $d_{S}:M\to \mathbb {R}$ defined by $d_{S}(x)=d(x,S)$ is continuous.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Incidentally, this shows that metric spaces are completely regular.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Given two subsets S and T of M, their *Hausdorff distance* is $d_{H}(S,T)=\max\{\sup\{d(s,T):s\in S\},\sup\{d(t,S):t\in T\}\}.$ Informally, two sets S and T are close to each other in the Hausdorff distance if no element of S is too far from T and vice versa.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, if S is an open set in Euclidean space T is an ε-net inside S, then $d_{H}(S,T)<\varepsilon$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In general, the Hausdorff distance $d_{H}(S,T)$ can be infinite or zero.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] However, the Hausdorff distance between two distinct compact sets is always positive and finite.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Thus the Hausdorff distance defines a metric on the set of compact subsets of M.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The Gromov–Hausdorff metric defines a distance between (isometry classes of) compact metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The *Gromov–Hausdorff distance* between compact spaces X and Y is the infimum of the Hausdorff distance over all metric spaces Z that contain X and Y as subspaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] While the exact value of the Gromov–Hausdorff distance is rarely useful to know, the resulting topology has found many applications.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] By the equivalence of norms in finite dimensions, a topologically equivalent metric is obtained if N is the taxicab norm, a p-norm, the maximum norm, or any other norm which is non-decreasing as the coordinates of a positive n-tuple increase (yielding the triangle inequality).
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The topological product of uncountably many metric spaces need not be metrizable.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, an uncountable product of copies of $\mathbb {R}$ is not first-countable and thus is not metrizable.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] If M is a metric space with metric d, and $\sim$ is an equivalence relation on M, then we can endow the quotient set $M/\!\sim$ with a pseudometric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] In general this will only define a pseudometric, i.e. $d'([x],[y])=0$ does not necessarily imply that $[x]=[y]$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] However, for some equivalence relations (e.g., those given by gluing together polyhedra along faces), $d'$ is a metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The quotient metric $d'$ is characterized by the following universal property.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] The quotient metric does not always induce the quotient topology.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] For example, the topological quotient of the metric space $\mathbb {N} \times [0,1]$ identifying all points of the form $(n,0)$ is not metrizable since it is not first-countable, but the quotient metric is a well-defined metric on the same set which induces a coarser topology.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] Moreover, different metrics on the original topological space (a disjoint union of countably many intervals) lead to different topologies on the quotient.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p01] A topological space is sequential if and only if it is a (topological) quotient of a metric space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] There are several notions of spaces which have less structure than a metric space, but more than a topological space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] There are also numerous ways of relaxing the axioms for a metric, giving rise to various notions of generalized metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] These generalizations can also be combined.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The terminology used to describe them is not completely standardized.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Most notably, in functional analysis pseudometrics often come from seminorms on vector spaces, and so it is natural to call them "semimetrics".
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] This conflicts with the use of the term in topology.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Some authors define metrics so as to allow the distance function d to attain the value ∞, i.e. distances are non-negative numbers on the extended real number line.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Such a function is also called an *extended metric* or "∞-metric".
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Every extended metric can be replaced by a real-valued metric that is topologically equivalent.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] This can be done using a subadditive monotonically increasing bounded function which is zero at zero, e.g. $d'(x,y)=d(x,y)/(1+d(x,y))$ or $d''(x,y)=\min(1,d(x,y))$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] These generalizations still induce a uniform structure on the space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] A *pseudometric* on X is a function $d:X\times X\to \mathbb {R}$ which satisfies the axioms for a metric, except that instead of the second (identity of indiscernibles) only $d(x,x)=0$ for all *x* is required.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] In some contexts, pseudometrics are referred to as *semimetrics* because of their relation to seminorms.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Occasionally, a **quasimetric** is defined as a function that satisfies all axioms for a metric with the possible exception of symmetry.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The name of this generalisation is not entirely standardized.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] For example, given a set X of mountain villages, the typical walking times between elements of X form a quasimetric because travel uphill takes longer than travel downhill.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Another example is the length of car rides in a city with one-way streets: here, a shortest path from point A to point B goes along a different set of streets than a shortest path from B to A and may have a different length.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] A quasimetric on the reals can be defined by setting $d(x,y)={\begin{cases}x-y&{\text{if }}x\geq y,\\1&{\text{otherwise.}}\end{cases}}$ The 1 may be replaced, for example, by infinity or by $1+{\sqrt {y-x}}$ or any other subadditive function of *y*-*x*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] This quasimetric describes the cost of modifying a metal stick: it is easy to reduce its size by filing it down, but it is difficult or impossible to grow it.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Given a quasimetric on X, one can define an R-ball around x to be the set $\{y\in X|d(x,y)\leq R\}$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] As in the case of a metric, such balls form a basis for a topology on X, but this topology need not be metrizable.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] For example, the topology induced by the quasimetric on the reals described above is the (reversed) Sorgenfrey line.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] In a *metametric*, all the axioms of a metric are satisfied except that the distance between identical points is not necessarily zero.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Metametrics appear in the study of Gromov hyperbolic metric spaces and their boundaries.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The *visual metametric* on such a space satisfies $d(x,x)=0$ for points x on the boundary, but otherwise $d(x,x)$ is approximately the distance from *x* to the boundary.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Metametrics were first defined by Jussi Väisälä.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] In other work, a function satisfying these axioms is called a *partial metric* or a *dislocated metric*.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The ρ-inframetric inequality implies the ρ-relaxed triangle inequality (assuming the first axiom), and the ρ-relaxed triangle inequality implies the 2ρ-inframetric inequality.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Semimetrics satisfying these equivalent conditions have sometimes been referred to as *quasimetrics*, *nearmetrics* or **inframetrics**.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The ρ-inframetric inequalities were introduced to model round-trip delay times in the internet.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The triangle inequality implies the 2-inframetric inequality, and the ultrametric inequality is exactly the 1-inframetric inequality.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Sometimes it is used to refer to other generalizations of metrics such as pseudosemimetrics or pseudometrics; in translations of Russian books it sometimes appears as "prametric".
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] A premetric that satisfies symmetry, i.e. a pseudosemimetric, is also called a distance.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Any premetric gives rise to a topology as follows.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] A set is called *open* if for any point *p* in the set there is an r -ball centered at *p* which is contained in the set.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Every premetric space is a topological space, and in fact a sequential space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] In general, the r -balls themselves need not be open sets with respect to this topology.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] This defines a premetric on the power set of a premetric space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] If we start with a (pseudosemi-)metric space, we get a pseudosemimetric, i.e. a symmetric premetric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The prefixes *pseudo-*, *quasi-* and *semi-* can also be combined, e.g., a **pseudoquasimetric** (sometimes called **hemimetric**) relaxes both the indiscernibility axiom and the symmetry axiom and is simply a premetric satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] For pseudoquasimetric spaces the open r -balls form a basis of open sets.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] A very basic example of a pseudoquasimetric space is the set $\{0,1\}$ with the premetric given by $d(0,1)=1$ and $d(1,0)=0.$ The associated topological space is the Sierpiński space.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Sets equipped with an extended pseudoquasimetric were studied by William Lawvere as "generalized metric spaces".
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] From a categorical point of view, the extended pseudometric spaces and the extended pseudoquasimetric spaces, along with their corresponding nonexpansive maps, are the best behaved of the metric space categories.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] One can take arbitrary products and coproducts and form quotient objects within the given category.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] If one drops "extended", one can only take finite products and coproducts.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] If one drops "pseudo", one cannot take quotients.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Lawvere also gave an alternate definition of such spaces as enriched categories.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The ordered set $(\mathbb {R} ,\geq )$ can be seen as a category with one morphism $a\to b$ if $a\geq b$ and none otherwise.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Using + as the tensor product and 0 as the identity makes this category into a monoidal category $R^{*}$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] The notion of a metric can be generalized from a distance between two elements to a number assigned to a multiset of elements.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] A multiset is a generalization of the notion of a set in which an element can occur more than once.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] Define the multiset union $U=XY$ as follows: if an element x occurs m times in X and n times in Y then it occurs *m* + *n* times in U.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] By considering the cases of axioms 1 and 2 in which the multiset X has two elements and the case of axiom 3 in which the multisets X, Y, and Z have one element each, one recovers the usual axioms for a metric.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] That is, every multiset metric yields an ordinary metric when restricted to sets of two elements.
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] A simple example is the set of all nonempty finite multisets X of integers with $d(X)=\max(X)-\min(X)$ .
[src:real-analysis/metric-space-p02] More complex examples are information distance in multisets; and normalized compression distance (NCD) in multisets.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The real numbers are the basic setting of real analysis, which begins with their construction.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The real numbers are distinguished from the rational numbers by their *completeness*.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Roughly speaking, the real numbers have no gaps.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This completeness can be formalized in several equivalent ways, one of which is the least upper bound property.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This states that if a non-empty set of real numbers is bounded above, meaning that all of its elements are less than some number (an upper bound), then there is a *least* upper bound, that is an upper bound that is smaller than all of the others.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Most of the theorems that are proved in real analysis rely on completeness in one way or another.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Some examples where its relevance are most apparent are as follows.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The convergence of bounded monotone sequences, that is sequences that are increasing (or decreasing), is essentially equivalent to the least upper bound property, stated in sequence form.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Completeness is also reflected in the intermediate value theorem: the continuous image of an interval is again an interval, so continuous functions cannot create gaps.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The concept of a limit underlies many of the ideas of calculus, such as the derivative.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] It is therefore of fundamental importance in real analysis, which provides the rigorous justification for calculus.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Limits describe how a sequence, function, or family of functions behave under a limiting process, such as letting an index tend to infinity, or a letting point become very large or approach another point.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The formal language of limits defines continuity, differentiation, integration, infinite series, and various kinds of approximations and asymptotics.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A recurring problem in real analysis is not just whether a limit exists, but how well one object approximates another.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A convergent sequence approximates its limit, or a differentiable function is approximated by a linear function coming from the derivative.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] But real analysis can provide not only tools to justify the existence of these limits and how to calculate them, but also quantitative estimates of how good the approximation is.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] One example of this is the Taylor remainder, which gives an effective and computable constant that determines how well the linear approximation (or higher-order Taylor polynomial) approximates a function on an interval.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] For sequences of functions, real analysis distinguishes between different modes of convergence.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A sequence of functions converges pointwise if it converges at every point, but, roughly speaking, the rate of convergence may vary from point to point.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] It converges uniformly if it converges at all points at a comparable rate.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Uniform convergence can be understood intuitively in terms of the graphs of the functions in the sequence: it means that, for any given thin error band around the limiting function, all but finitely many functions in the sequence stay within the band.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Pointwise convergence means that this is true for an error band around each point, but the finite set of functions which must be excluded varies from point to point.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] For sequences of functions, pointwise convergence often fails to preserve operations on the limit function.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] For example, it is not generally true that the pointwise limit of a sequence of continuous functions is continuous, or that the integral of the functions in a sequence passes to the integral of the limit function.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] But the *uniform* limit of continuous functions is continuous, and one can exchange integration and uniform limits on suitable domains.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Uniform convergence is therefore important for many applications of real analysis.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Questions such as "when is differentiation under the integral allowed?" or "when can I integrate an infinite sum term-by-term?" are typical examples in which uniform convergence provides a simple answer.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Differentiation measures the local rate of change of a function.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In one variable, the derivative gives the slope of the best linear approximation to a function near a point.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This point of view extends to several variables, where differentiability is expressed in terms of approximation by a linear map.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In addition to proving rigorously the fundamental properties of the derivative from calculus, such as the chain rule, real analysis also establishes the main theorems about the derivative, such as the mean value theorem and some of its generalizations like the Cauchy mean value theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Roughly speaking, the mean value theorem relates the derivative of a function to its average rate of change over intervals.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The mean value theorem is important because it leads to an effective way to estimate the error in certain approximations or averaging processes.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Real analysis studies not only existence of derivatives, but also degrees of regularity.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A function may be continuous but nowhere differentiable, differentiable but not continuously differentiable, or smooth (having derivatives of all orders) but not analytic (equal to its Taylor series).
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] One theorem that is sometimes shown at the elementary level is Darboux's theorem, that the derivative of a differentiable function satisfies the intermediate value property; weaker than continuity, but still a restricted class of functions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In more advanced analysis, regularity questions become central.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The classical derivative turns out to be very inconvenient in many applications, such as to differential equations where many problems have a more natural variational formulation using integration rather than differentiation.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The functions one must consider are often not differentiable, and so generalizations of differentiability, and even what constitutes a function, are considered.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Regularity then involves questions about whether the generalized derivatives are honest derivatives, and how smooth solutions to equations are.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This is a common theme in measure theory, partial differential equations, Sobolev spaces, and the calculus of variations.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Integration in analysis gives rigorous meaning to averaging, accumulation, and area.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The Riemann integral formalizes the integral using approximations by finite sums over intervals.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The Riemann integral is put on a firm foundation in basic real analysis courses.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The fundamental theorem of calculus, which relates integration and differentiation, is proved for the Riemann integral.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The fundamental theorem underlies many exact computations in elementary integral calculus by reducing definite integrals to antiderivatives.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The mean value theorem for integration states that the average value of a continuous function over an interval, defined by a Riemann integral, is equal to the value of the function at some point inside the interval.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The mean value theorem is important in deriving analytic estimates in analytic applications; for example, one form of the Taylor remainder uses it.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The Lebesgue integral is introduced in more advanced real analysis.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Instead of approximating the integral by finite sums using partitions of the domain, the Lebesgue integral partitions the range instead.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] While the idea is similar to the Riemann integral, it differs from the Riemann integral in that one must formulate the area of horizontal slabs that are not connected rectangles, but may be distributed over complicated sets in the domain.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Thus formulating the Lebesgue integral leads naturally to measure theory, the fundamental question of which is how to measure subsets of the real line – that is, assign a notion of length – if the subsets are allowed to be very complicated.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] One reason for the success of the Lebesgue integral in analysis is that it is more compatible with limiting processes.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] For example, under relatively mild hypotheses, the limit of the Lebesgue integrals of members of a sequence of functions that converges only pointwise is equal to the integral of the pointwise limit (dominated convergence theorem).
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Moreover, the Lebesgue integral admits a wider class of functions as integrable.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The Riemann integral, although not widely used in mathematical analysis, still has its uses however: most numerical integration relies on the Riemann rather than Lebesgue approach to integration.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Measure theory treats length, area, volume, mass, and probability as instances of a general concept of measure.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The theory allows one to identify functions that are equal except on a set of measure zero, and one says that such functions are equal almost everywhere.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In probability theory, the relevant notion is almost surely.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] An example is tossing a fair coin an infinite sequence of times.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] It is *possible* that the coin could come up tails every time, but this event has zero probability: it can be essentially excluded from any probabilistic argument.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The monotone convergence theorem, Fatou's lemma, dominated convergence theorem, and Fubini's theorem are basic theorems about the Lebesgue integral.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Measure-theoretic real analysis also supplies the language of probability and of many function spaces.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In probability theory, expected values are integrals with respect to probability measures.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In the theory of L*p* spaces, functions are studied according to integrability properties and are identified when they agree almost everywhere.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Infinite series are one of the basic limiting processes of real analysis.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A numerical series is defined by the convergence of its partial sums, and questions about its absolute convergence, conditional convergence, and rearrangements illustrate the difference between finite and infinite additions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Power series and Taylor series connect infinite series with differentiablity and analyticity.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Sequences and series are used to approximate and represent functions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Uniform convergence gives conditions under which continuity, integrability, and sometimes differentiability, pass to the limit function.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Power series can be used to represent some functions locally, while Fourier series represent periodic functions in terms of trigonometric series.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Many of the theorems of real analysis can be formulated in metric spaces.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Metric spaces generalize the real line and Euclidean spaces, in the sense that they have a notion of distance function defined on them that satisfies some natural rules.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The basic theorems about limits and continuity carry through, essentially unchanged, in the more general setting, and so elementary treatments of the subject often describe this generalization.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The generalizations to metric spaces are important in many areas of mathematics.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] One example of a metric space is a surface in Euclidean space.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The analytic properties of metrics like this are similar to those of Euclidean space, and differential geometry involves the study of metric spaces like surfaces and their generalizations to higher dimensions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Other metric spaces in mathematics are very different from Euclidean spaces.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In number theory for example, metric spaces are used to encode arithmetic information and invariants, a basic example of which is the p-adic numbers.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In real analysis proper, most of the examples of metric spaces other than Euclidean spaces are function spaces, that is spaces of functions that are defined by some property.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In the basic examples considered in real analysis, these spaces of functions have a metric that comes from a norm.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] An example is the space of continuous functions on the unit interval, denoted $C([0,1])$ .
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Given a real-valued function on the unit interval, the maximum absolute value of the function defines the norm.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The metric is the maximum absolute difference between two functions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The notion of convergence that this metric defines is that of uniform convergence, so that the language of uniform convergence of continuous functions can be packaged into a single metric space.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This is an example of a Banach space: the metric that this norm defines is complete, which is a consequence of a theorem that the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Another example of metric spaces appearing in real analysis, where the metric comes from a norm, is the space $L^{1}$ of Lebesgue integrable functions, and the distance function is the integral of the absolute value of the difference of two functions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] (Here functions are regarded as the same if they differ on a set of measure zero.) Thus, on a finite domain, the distance between two functions is essentially the average distance between their values.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Spaces of square integrable measurable functions form a metric space, where the norm is induced by an inner product.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This inner product is complete: the square integrable functions are a Hilbert space.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The L*p* spaces are generalizations of these.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The metrics one gets from the L*p* spaces are complete: they are Banach spaces, with the usual identification of measurable functions that are equal almost everywhere.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] These function spaces, while all being infinite dimensional vector spaces, and share similar kinds of convergence theorems because they are all metric spaces, are different both globally as spaces, and locally in terms of the fine structure that functions must carry for membership.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Functional analysis is concerned with these spaces and their generalizations, their global and convergence properties.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Harmonic analysis is concerned with the fine properties needed for membership, and to estimate how operators determined by fine structure behave in theses spaces: a typical question here is to characterize when the derivative of a function is in a certain L*p* space, for example..
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Many applications of metric spaces to analysis rely on a metric space with extra properties that ensure that certain limits exist and belong to the space.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] One such property is whether a metric space is complete, and another is whether a metric space is compact.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Completeness of a space is formulated in terms of Cauchy sequences within it.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A sequence in a space *converges* to a limit if all except finitely many of its members are arbitrarily close to the limit.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Now, if a sequence converges, then all but finitely many of its members are close to the limit, and therefore must be close to one another.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This property characterizes the Cauchy sequences in a metric space.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Stated a little more carefully, a sequence is Cauchy if, for any error tolerance, all but finitely many members lie within that error tolerance of each other.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A metric space is complete if every Cauchy sequence converges.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The real numbers, for example, are complete in this sense.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] One key theorem for complete metric spaces is the contraction mapping theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This theorem is particularly important in differential equations, because it supplies the basic existence and uniqueness theorem for solutions of ordinary differential equations – the Picard existence theorem – as well as a method for converging to it – Picard iteration.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Furthermore, it provides estimates of the rate of convergence, provided one can determine the contractivity constant C .
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Another notion in metric spaces is compactness.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A metric space is compact if every sequence has a convergent subsequence.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Compact metric spaces are also complete, but compactness is useful for guaranteeing the existence of limits without needing to study a separate Cauchy condition.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In basic real analysis, the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem shows that a subset of Euclidean space is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A more general notion of compactness applies to general topological spaces that are not necessarily metric spaces, and it is based on the idea that compact spaces should generalized finite sets.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Finite sets have the property that whenever they are covered by a family of subsets, so that every member of the set belongs to some member of the cover, it is possible to cover the finite set with a finite subfamily.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] For example, one can pick from each element of the finite set one member of the covering family that contains it.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A metric space is compact in this sense if every covering by open sets has a finite subcover.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] An example of a compact set in this sense is a closed interval $[a,b]$ : whenever this set is covered by open intervals, it is possible to cover it with finitely many of the intervals.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This can be shown by a straightforward application of the least upper bound property.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] A compact set in the real line can be shown to be bounded, by considering an open cover by intervals $(-n,n)$ and using a finite subcover to extract a bound.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] It can also be shown to be closed by a simple proof by contradiction.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Another foundational result in real analysis is the Heine–Borel theorem, which states the converse to this: a subset of the real line (or Euclidean space, more generally) is compact in this sense *if and only if* it is closed and bounded.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Compactness plays an important role through its interaction with continuity.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The extreme value theorem in calculus, for example, says that a continuous function on a closed interval $[a,b]$ attains both a maximum and minimum value.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In real analysis, this generalizes: any continuous real-valued function on a compact metric space attains both a maximum and minimum value.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This result is important in optimization theory because it guarantees the existence of maxima and minima, often in very general situations where compactness is present but one is no longer working on subsets of the real line (or other Euclidean space).
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Another theorem in real analysis, relating to compactness and continuous functions, is the Arzelà–Ascoli theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] It asserts that if a sequence of continuous functions on a compact metric space is uniformly bounded (all functions share a common upper and lower bound) and equicontinuous (all functions share a common modulus of continuity), then the sequence of functions has a uniformly convergent subsequence.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] This theorem has applications to differential equations, because it can be used to guarantee existence of solutions to differential equations where the stricter criteria of the Picard existence theorem do not hold.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] An example application is the Peano existence theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The Arzelà–Ascoli theorem is itself a kind of compactness assertion, characterizing compactness in the Banach space of functions on a compact metric space.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Important elementary results put the techniques of calculus on rigorous footing.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] They include the Bolzano–Weierstrass and Heine–Borel theorems, L'Hopital's rule, the mean value theorem, Taylor's theorem, the fundamental theorem of calculus, and the extreme value theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Other results, also taught in an elementary course, are motivated by applications, chiefly to differential equations, multivariable calculus, and Fourier analysis which are part of the undergraduate mathematics curriculum.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] They are the Arzelà-Ascoli theorem, the Stone-Weierstrass theorem, the Banach fixed-point theorem, the inverse and implicit function theorems, and Stokes' theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] More advanced graduate-level courses also cover the basics of measure theory, the basic theorems of which are: Egorov's theorem, Lusin's theorem, Fatou's lemma, the monotone and dominated convergence theorems, and Fubini's theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Other advanced results are sometimes also covered at the graduate level, because these are motivated by applications to other areas in the graduate curriculum.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] They include the Radon–Nikodym theorem, Lebesgue decomposition theorem, and Riesz representation theorem.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Sometimes results such as the Lebesgue differentiation theorem are also included, as applications of harmonic analysis to questions of real analysis.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Various ideas from real analysis can be generalized from the real line to broader or more abstract contexts.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] These generalizations link real analysis to other disciplines and subdisciplines.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Georg Cantor's investigation of sets and sequence of real numbers, mappings between them, and the foundational issues of real analysis gave birth to naive set theory.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] The study of issues of convergence for sequences of functions eventually gave rise to Fourier analysis as a subdiscipline of mathematical analysis.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Investigation of the consequences of generalizing differentiability from functions of a real variable to ones of a complex variable gave rise to the concept of holomorphic functions and the inception of complex analysis as another distinct subdiscipline of analysis.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] On the other hand, the generalization of integration from the Riemann sense to that of Lebesgue led to the formulation of the concept of abstract measure spaces, a fundamental concept in measure theory.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Real analysis is an area of analysis that studies concepts such as sequences and their limits, continuity, differentiation, integration and sequences of functions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] By definition, real analysis focuses on the real numbers, often including positive and negative infinity to form the extended real line.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Real analysis is closely related to complex analysis, which studies broadly the same properties of complex numbers.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In complex analysis, it is natural to define differentiation via holomorphic functions, which have a number of useful properties, such as repeated differentiability, expressibility as power series, and satisfying the Cauchy integral formula.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] In real analysis, it is usually more natural to consider differentiable, smooth, or harmonic functions, which are more widely applicable, but may lack some more powerful properties of holomorphic functions.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] However, results such as the fundamental theorem of algebra are simpler when expressed in terms of complex numbers.
[src:real-analysis/real-analysis] Techniques from the theory of analytic functions of a complex variable are often used in real analysis – such as evaluation of real integrals by residue calculus.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In real analysis, the **Riemann integral** is a rigorous definition of the integral of a function on an interval.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] It defines the integral by approximating the region under the graph of a function by finite sums of areas of vertical rectangles.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] For suitable functions, including every continuous function on a closed bounded interval, these Riemann sums approach a single limiting value as the partitions of the interval become finer.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] That limiting value defines the integral, and Riemann sums that are suitably close to the limit can be used as numerical approximations.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Bernhard Riemann introduced the integral in work presented to the faculty at the University of Göttingen in 1854 and published in 1868.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] It is the integral most commonly introduced in elementary calculus, although in advanced analysis it is often replaced by more general notions such as the Lebesgue integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Consider a curve on a graph which stays above the *x*-axis, beginning at *x* = *a* and ending at *x* = *b*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The area under that curve, from *a* to *b*, is what we want to find.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This area can be described as the set of all points (*x*, *y*) on the graph that follow these rules: *a* ≤ *x* ≤ *b* (the *x*-coordinate is between *a* and *b*) and 0 < *y* < *f*(*x*) (the *y*-coordinate is between 0 and the height of the curve *f*(*x*)).
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This notation means “the integral of *f*(*x*) from *a* to *b*,” and it represents the exact area under the curve *f*(*x*) and above the *x*-axis, between *x* = *a* and *x* = *b*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The idea behind the Riemann integral is to break the area into small, simple shapes (like rectangles), add up their areas, and then make the rectangles smaller and smaller to get a better estimate.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In the end, when the rectangles are infinitely small, the sum gives the exact area, which is what the integral represents.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If the curve dips below the *x*-axis, the integral gives a **signed area**.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This means the integral adds the part above the *x*-axis as positive and subtracts the part below the *x*-axis as negative.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] So, the result of $\int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx$ can be positive, negative, or zero, depending on how much of the curve is above or below the *x*-axis.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Each [*xi*, *x**i* + 1] is called a **sub-interval** of the partition.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] A **tagged partition** *P*(*x*, *t*) of an interval [*a*, *b*] is a partition together with a choice of a sample point within each sub-interval: that is, numbers *t*0, ..., *t**n* − 1 with *ti* ∈ [*xi*, *x**i* + 1] for each i.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The mesh of a tagged partition is the same as that of an ordinary partition.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] A partition Q is said to refine the a partition P if the intervals in the partition Q are all subintervals of the intervals in the partition P , so that the points marking the partition in Q include those of P and possibly others making it finer.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] A refinement of a tagged partition is defined so that each tag $t_{i}$ of P is a tag of some interval in Q .
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] We can turn the set of all tagged partitions into a directed set by saying that one tagged partition is greater than or equal to another if the former is a refinement of the latter.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] A sequence of Riemann sums over a regular partition of an interval.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The number on top is the total area of the rectangles, which converges to the integral of the function.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The partition does not need to be regular, as shown here.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The approximation works as long as the width of each subdivision tends to zero.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Let f be a real-valued function defined on the interval [*a*, *b*].
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Each term in the sum is the product of the value of the function at a given point and the length of an interval.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Consequently, each term represents the (signed) area of a rectangle with height *f*(*ti*) and width *x**i* + 1 − *xi*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The Riemann sum is the (signed) area of all the rectangles.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Closely related concepts are the *lower and upper Darboux sums*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If f is continuous, then the lower and upper Darboux sums for an untagged partition are equal to the Riemann sum for that partition, where the tags are chosen to be the minimum or maximum (respectively) of f on each subinterval.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] (When f is discontinuous on a subinterval, there may not be a tag that achieves the infimum or supremum on that subinterval.) The Darboux integral, which is similar to the Riemann integral but based on Darboux sums, is equivalent to the Riemann integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Loosely speaking, the Riemann integral is the limit of the Riemann sums of a function as the partitions get finer.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If the limit exists then the function is said to be **integrable** (or more specifically **Riemann-integrable**).
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The Riemann sum can be made as close as desired to the Riemann integral by making the partition fine enough.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] One important requirement is that the mesh of the partitions must become smaller and smaller, so that it has the limit zero.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If this were not so, then we would not be getting a good approximation to the function on certain subintervals.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In fact, this is enough to define an integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Unfortunately, this definition is very difficult to use.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] It would help to develop an equivalent definition of the Riemann integral which is easier to work with.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] We develop this definition now, with a proof of equivalence following.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Both of these mean that eventually, the Riemann sum of f with respect to any partition gets trapped close to s.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Since this is true no matter how close we demand the sums be trapped, we say that the Riemann sums converge to s.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] These definitions are actually a special case of a more general concept, a net.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] As we stated earlier, these two definitions are equivalent.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In other words, s works in the first definition if and only if s works in the second definition.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] To show that the first definition implies the second, start with an ε, and choose a δ that satisfies the condition.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Choose any tagged partition whose mesh is less than δ.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Its Riemann sum is within ε of s, and any refinement of this partition will also have mesh less than δ, so the Riemann sum of the refinement will also be within ε of s.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] To show that the second definition implies the first, it is easiest to use the Darboux integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] First, one shows that the second definition is equivalent to the definition of the Darboux integral; for this see the Darboux integral article.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Now we will show that a Darboux integrable function satisfies the first definition.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Fix ε, and choose a partition *y*0, ..., *ym* such that the lower and upper Darboux sums with respect to this partition are within *ε*/2 of the value s of the Darboux integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If *r* = 0, then f is the zero function, which is clearly both Darboux and Riemann integrable with integral zero.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If *m* = 1, then we choose δ to be less than one.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Choose a tagged partition *x*0, ..., *xn* and *t*0, ..., *t**n* − 1 with mesh smaller than δ.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] We must show that the Riemann sum is within ε of s.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] To see this, choose an interval [*xi*, *x**i* + 1].
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If this interval is contained within some [*yj*, *y**j* + 1], then $m_{j}\leq f(t_{i})\leq M_{j}$ where mj and Mj are respectively, the infimum and the supremum of *f* on [*yj*, *y**j* + 1].
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If all intervals had this property, then this would conclude the proof, because each term in the Riemann sum would be bounded by a corresponding term in the Darboux sums, and we chose the Darboux sums to be near s.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This is the case when *m* = 1, so the proof is finished in that case.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In this case, it is possible that one of the [*xi*, *x**i* + 1] is not contained in any [*yj*, *y**j* + 1].
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Instead, it may stretch across two of the intervals determined by *y*0, ..., *ym*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] (We may assume that all the inequalities are strict because otherwise we are in the previous case by our assumption on the length of δ.) This can happen at most *m* − 1 times.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] To handle this case, we will estimate the difference between the Riemann sum and the Darboux sum by subdividing the partition *x*0, ..., *xn* at *y**j* + 1.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Suppose, without loss of generality, that *ti* ∈ [*yj*, *y**j* + 1].
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Then $m_{j}\leq f(t_{i})\leq M_{j},$ so this term is bounded by the corresponding term in the Darboux sum for yj.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Since this happens at most *m* − 1 times, the distance between the Riemann sum and a Darboux sum is at most *ε*/2.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Therefore, the distance between the Riemann sum and s is at most ε.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Let $f:[0,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ be the function which takes the value 1 at every point.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Any Riemann sum of f on [0, 1] will have the value 1, therefore the Riemann integral of f on [0, 1] is 1.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Let $I_{\mathbb {Q} }:[0,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ be the indicator function of the rational numbers in [0, 1]; that is, $I_{\mathbb {Q} }$ takes the value 1 on rational numbers and 0 on irrational numbers.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This function does not have a Riemann integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] To prove this, we will show how to construct tagged partitions whose Riemann sums get arbitrarily close to both zero and one.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The ti have already been chosen, and we can't change the value of f at those points.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] But if we cut the partition into tiny pieces around each ti, we can minimize the effect of the ti.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Then, by carefully choosing the new tags, we can make the value of the Riemann sum turn out to be within ε of either zero or one.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Our first step is to cut up the partition.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] There are n of the ti, and we want their total effect to be less than ε.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If we confine each of them to an interval of length less than *ε*/*n*, then the contribution of each ti to the Riemann sum will be at least 0 · *ε*/*n* and at most 1 · *ε*/*n*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This makes the total sum at least zero and at most ε.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] So let δ be a positive number less than *ε*/*n*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If it happens that two of the ti are within δ of each other, choose δ smaller.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If it happens that some ti is within δ of some xj, and ti is not equal to xj, choose δ smaller.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Since there are only finitely many ti and xj, we can always choose δ sufficiently small.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Now we add two cuts to the partition for each ti.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] One of the cuts will be at *ti* − *δ*/2, and the other will be at *ti* + *δ*/2.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] We still have to choose tags for the other subintervals.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] We will choose them in two different ways.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The first way is to always choose a rational point, so that the Riemann sum is as large as possible.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This will make the value of the Riemann sum at least 1 − *ε*.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The second way is to always choose an irrational point, so that the Riemann sum is as small as possible.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This will make the value of the Riemann sum at most ε.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Since we started from an arbitrary partition and ended up as close as we wanted to either zero or one, it is false to say that we are eventually trapped near some number s, so this function is not Riemann integrable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In the Lebesgue sense its integral is zero, since the function is zero almost everywhere.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] But this is a fact that is beyond the reach of the Riemann integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] There are even worse examples. $I_{\mathbb {Q} }$ is equivalent (that is, equal almost everywhere) to a Riemann integrable function, but there are non-Riemann integrable bounded functions which are not equivalent to any Riemann integrable function.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] For example, let C be the Smith–Volterra–Cantor set, and let *IC* be its indicator function.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Because C is not Jordan measurable, *IC* is not Riemann integrable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Moreover, no function g equivalent to *IC* is Riemann integrable: g, like *IC*, must be zero on a dense set, so as in the previous example, any Riemann sum of g has a refinement which is within ε of 0 for any positive number ε.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] But if the Riemann integral of g exists, then it must equal the Lebesgue integral of *IC*, which is 1/2.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] It is popular to define the Riemann integral as the Darboux integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This is because the Darboux integral is technically simpler and because a function is Riemann-integrable if and only if it is Darboux-integrable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Some calculus books do not use general tagged partitions, but limit themselves to specific types of tagged partitions.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If the type of partition is limited too much, some non-integrable functions may appear to be integrable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] One popular restriction is the use of "left-hand" and "right-hand" Riemann sums.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In a left-hand Riemann sum, *ti* = *xi* for all i, and in a right-hand Riemann sum, *ti* = *x**i* + 1 for all i.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Alone this restriction does not impose a problem: we can refine any partition in a way that makes it a left-hand or right-hand sum by subdividing it at each ti.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In more formal language, the set of all left-hand Riemann sums and the set of all right-hand Riemann sums is cofinal in the set of all tagged partitions.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Another popular restriction is the use of regular subdivisions of an interval.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Again, alone this restriction does not impose a problem, but the reasoning required to see this fact is more difficult than in the case of left-hand and right-hand Riemann sums.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] However, combining these restrictions, so that one uses only left-hand or right-hand Riemann sums on regularly divided intervals, is dangerous.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If a function is known in advance to be Riemann integrable, then this technique will give the correct value of the integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The problem with this definition becomes apparent when we try to split the integral into two pieces.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If we use regular subdivisions and left-hand or right-hand Riemann sums, then the two terms on the left are equal to zero, since every endpoint except 0 and 1 will be irrational, but as we have seen the term on the right will equal 1.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] As defined above, the Riemann integral avoids this problem by refusing to integrate $I_{\mathbb {Q} }.$ The Lebesgue integral is defined in such a way that all these integrals are 0.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Because the Riemann integral of a function is a number, this makes the Riemann integral a linear functional on the vector space of Riemann-integrable functions.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] A bounded function on a compact interval [*a*, *b*] is Riemann integrable if and only if it is continuous almost everywhere (the set of its points of discontinuity has measure zero, in the sense of Lebesgue measure).
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This is the **Lebesgue-Vitali theorem** (of characterization of the Riemann integrable functions).
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] It has been proven independently by Giuseppe Vitali and by Henri Lebesgue in 1907, and uses the notion of measure zero, but makes use of neither Lebesgue's general measure or integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The integrability condition can be proven in various ways, one of which is sketched below.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In particular, any set that is at most countable has Lebesgue measure zero, and thus a bounded function (on a compact interval) with only finitely or countably many discontinuities is Riemann integrable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Another sufficient criterion to Riemann integrability over [*a*, *b*], but which does not involve the concept of measure, is the existence of a right-hand (or left-hand) limit at *every* point in [*a*, *b*) (or (*a*, *b*]).
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] An indicator function of a bounded set is Riemann-integrable if and only if the set is Jordan measurable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The Riemann integral can be interpreted measure-theoretically as the integral with respect to the Jordan measure.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If a real-valued function is monotone on the interval [*a*, *b*] it is Riemann integrable, since its set of discontinuities is at most countable, and therefore of Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If a real-valued function on [*a*, *b*] is Riemann integrable, it is Lebesgue integrable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] That is, Riemann-integrability is a *stronger* (meaning more difficult to satisfy) condition than Lebesgue-integrability.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The converse does not hold; not all Lebesgue-integrable functions are Riemann integrable.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The Lebesgue–Vitali theorem does not imply that all type of discontinuities have the same weight on the obstruction that a real-valued bounded function be Riemann integrable on [*a*, *b*].
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In fact, certain discontinuities have absolutely no role on the Riemann integrability of the function—a consequence of the classification of the discontinuities of a function.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] However, the Lebesgue monotone convergence theorem (on a monotone pointwise limit) does not hold for Riemann integrals.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Thus, in Riemann integration, taking limits under the integral sign is far more difficult to logically justify than in Lebesgue integration.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] It is easy to extend the Riemann integral to functions with values in the Euclidean vector space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ for any n.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In particular, since the complex numbers are a real vector space, this allows the integration of complex valued functions.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The Riemann integral is only defined on bounded intervals, and it does not extend well to unbounded intervals.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] For example, consider the sign function *f*(*x*) = sgn(*x*) which is 0 at *x* = 0, 1 for *x* > 0, and −1 for *x* < 0.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] But there are many ways for the interval of integration to expand to fill the real line, and other ways can produce different results; in other words, the multivariate limit does not always exist.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In general, this improper Riemann integral is undefined.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Even standardizing a way for the interval to approach the real line does not work because it leads to disturbingly counterintuitive results.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] If we agree (for instance) that the improper integral should always be $\lim _{a\to \infty }\int _{-a}^{a}f(x)\,dx,$ then the integral of the translation *f*(*x* − 1) is −2, so this definition is not invariant under shifts, a highly undesirable property.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In fact, not only does this function not have an improper Riemann integral, its Lebesgue integral is also undefined (it equals ∞ − ∞).
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Unfortunately, the improper Riemann integral is not powerful enough.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The most severe problem is that there are no widely applicable theorems for commuting improper Riemann integrals with limits of functions.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In applications such as Fourier series it is important to be able to approximate the integral of a function using integrals of approximations to the function.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] On non-compact intervals such as the real line, this is false.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] For example, take *fn*(*x*) to be *n*−1 on [0, *n*] and zero elsewhere.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The sequence (*fn*) converges uniformly to the zero function, and clearly the integral of the zero function is zero.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This demonstrates that for integrals on unbounded intervals, uniform convergence of a function is not strong enough to allow passing a limit through an integral sign.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] A better route is to abandon the Riemann integral for the Lebesgue integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The definition of the Lebesgue integral is not obviously a generalization of the Riemann integral, but it is not hard to prove that every Riemann-integrable function is Lebesgue-integrable and that the values of the two integrals agree whenever they are both defined.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Moreover, a function f defined on a bounded interval is Riemann-integrable if and only if it is bounded and the set of points where f is discontinuous has Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] An integral which is in fact a direct generalization of the Riemann integral is the Henstock–Kurzweil integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Another way of generalizing the Riemann integral is to replace the factors *x**k* + 1 − *x**k* in the definition of a Riemann sum by something else; roughly speaking, this gives the interval of integration a different notion of length.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] This is the approach taken by the Riemann–Stieltjes integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In multivariable calculus, the Riemann integrals for functions from $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ are multiple integrals.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The Riemann integral is unsuitable for many theoretical purposes.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Some of the technical deficiencies in Riemann integration can be remedied with the Riemann–Stieltjes integral, and most disappear with the Lebesgue integral, though the latter does not have a satisfactory treatment of improper integrals.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The gauge integral is a generalisation of the Lebesgue integral that is at the same time closer to the Riemann integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] These more general theories allow for the integration of more "jagged" or "highly oscillating" functions whose Riemann integral does not exist; but the theories give the same value as the Riemann integral when it does exist.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] In educational settings, the Darboux integral offers a simpler definition that is easier to work with; it can be used to introduce the Riemann integral.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] The Darboux integral is defined whenever the Riemann integral is, and always gives the same result.
[src:real-analysis/riemann-integral] Conversely, the gauge integral is a simple but more powerful generalization of the Riemann integral and has led some educators to advocate that it should replace the Riemann integral in introductory calculus courses.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **series** is, roughly speaking, an addition of infinitely many terms, one after the other.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The study of series is a major part of calculus and its generalization, mathematical analysis.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Series are used in most areas of mathematics, even for studying finite structures in combinatorics through generating functions.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The mathematical properties of infinite series make them widely applicable in other quantitative disciplines such as physics, computer science, statistics and finance.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Among the Ancient Greeks, the idea that a potentially infinite summation could produce a finite result was considered paradoxical, most famously in Zeno's paradoxes.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Nonetheless, infinite series were applied practically by Ancient Greek mathematicians including Archimedes, for instance in the quadrature of the parabola.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The mathematical side of Zeno's paradoxes was resolved using the concept of a limit during the 17th century, especially through the early calculus of Isaac Newton.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In modern terminology, any ordered infinite sequence $(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},\ldots )$ of terms, whether those terms are numbers, functions, matrices, or anything else that can be added, defines a series, which is the addition of the ⁠ $a_{i}$ ⁠ one after the other.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] To emphasize that there are an infinite number of terms, series are often also called **infinite series** to contrast with finite series, a term sometimes used for finite sums.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The infinite sequence of additions expressed by a series cannot be explicitly performed in sequence in a finite amount of time.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] However, if the terms and their finite sums belong to a set that has limits, it may be possible to assign a value to a series, called the **sum of the series**.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] This value is the limit as ⁠ n ⁠ tends to infinity of the finite sums of the ⁠ n ⁠ first terms of the series if the limit exists.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] These finite sums are called the **partial sums** of the series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When the limit exists, the series is **convergent** or **summable** and also the sequence $(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},\ldots )$ is **summable**, and otherwise, when the limit does not exist, the series is **divergent**.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The expression ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{\infty }a_{i}}$ denotes both the series—the implicit process of adding the terms one after the other indefinitely—and, if the series is convergent, the sum of the series—the explicit limit of the process.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] This is a generalization of the similar convention of denoting by $a+b$ both the addition—the process of adding—and its result—the *sum* of ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Commonly, the terms of a series come from a ring, often the field $\mathbb {R}$ of the real numbers or the field $\mathbb {C}$ of the complex numbers.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] If so, the set of all series is also itself a ring, one in which the addition consists of adding series terms together term by term and the multiplication is the Cauchy product.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] A *series* or, redundantly, an *infinite series*, is an infinite sum.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] It is often represented as $a_{0}+a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots \quad {\text{or}}\quad a_{1}+a_{2}+a_{3}+\cdots ,$ where the terms $a_{k}$ are the members of a sequence of numbers, functions, or anything else that can be added.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Some authors directly identify a series with its sequence of partial sums.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Partial summation of a sequence is an example of a linear sequence transformation, and it is also known as the prefix sum in computer science.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The inverse transformation for recovering a sequence from its partial sums is the finite difference, another linear sequence transformation.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Strictly speaking, a series is said to *converge*, to be *convergent*, or to be *summable* when the sequence of its partial sums has a limit.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When the limit of the sequence of partial sums does not exist, the series *diverges* or is *divergent*.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When the limit of the partial sums exists, it is called the *sum of the series* or *value of the series*: $\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }a_{k}=\lim _{n\to \infty }\sum _{k=0}^{n}a_{k}=\lim _{n\to \infty }s_{n}.$ A series with only a finite number of nonzero terms is always convergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Such series are useful for considering finite sums without taking care of the numbers of terms.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When the sum exists, the difference between the sum of a series and its n th partial sum, ${\textstyle s-s_{n}=\sum _{k=n+1}^{\infty }a_{k},}$ is known as the n th *truncation error* of the infinite series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] By contrast, the geometric series $\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }2^{k}$ is divergent in the real numbers.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] However, it is convergent in the extended real number line, with $+\infty$ as its limit and $+\infty$ as its truncation error at every step.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When a series's sequence of partial sums is not easily calculated and evaluated for convergence directly, convergence tests can be used to prove that the series converges or diverges.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] For example, Grandi's series ⁠ $1-1+1-1+\cdots$ ⁠ has a sequence of partial sums that alternates back and forth between ⁠ 1 ⁠ and ⁠ 0 ⁠ and does not converge.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Grouping its elements in pairs creates the series $(1-1)+(1-1)+(1-1)+\cdots ={}$ $0+0+0+\cdots ,$ which has partial sums equal to zero at every term and thus sums to zero.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Grouping its elements in pairs starting after the first creates the series $1+(-1+1)+{}$ $(-1+1)+\cdots ={}$ $1+0+0+\cdots ,$ which has partial sums equal to one for every term and thus sums to one, a different result.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In general, grouping the terms of a series creates a new series with a sequence of partial sums that is a subsequence of the partial sums of the original series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] This means that if the original series converges, so does the new series after grouping: all infinite subsequences of a convergent sequence also converge to the same limit.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] However, if the original series diverges, then the grouped series do not necessarily diverge, as in this example of Grandi's series above.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] However, divergence of a grouped series does imply the original series must be divergent, since it proves there is a subsequence of the partial sums of the original series which is not convergent, which would be impossible if it were convergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] This reasoning was applied in Oresme's proof of the divergence of the harmonic series, and it is the basis for the general Cauchy condensation test.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] However, as for grouping, an infinitary rearrangement of terms of a series can sometimes lead to a change in the limit of the partial sums of the series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Series with sequences of partial sums that converge to a value but whose terms could be rearranged to a form a series with partial sums that converge to some other value are called conditionally convergent series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Those that converge to the same value regardless of rearrangement are called unconditionally convergent series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] For series of real numbers and complex numbers, a series $a_{0}+a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots$ is unconditionally convergent if and only if the series summing the absolute values of its terms, $|a_{0}|+|a_{1}|+|a_{2}|+\cdots ,$ is also convergent, a property called absolute convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Otherwise, any series of real numbers or complex numbers that converges but does not converge absolutely is conditionally convergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Any conditionally convergent sum of real numbers can be rearranged to yield any other real number as a limit, or to diverge.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] These claims are the content of the Riemann series theorem.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] By the Riemann series theorem, rearrangements of the alternating harmonic series to yield any other real number are also possible.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Therefore, first, the series resulting from addition is summable if the series added were summable, and, second, the sum of the resulting series is the addition of the sums of the added series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The addition of two divergent series may yield a convergent series: for instance, the addition of a divergent series with a series of its terms times $-1$ will yield a series of all zeros that converges to zero.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] However, for any two series where one converges and the other diverges, the result of their addition diverges.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] For series of real numbers or complex numbers, series addition is associative, commutative, and invertible.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Therefore series addition gives the sets of convergent series of real numbers or complex numbers the structure of an abelian group and also gives the sets of all series of real numbers or complex numbers (regardless of convergence properties) the structure of an abelian group.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Therefore if a series is summable, any nonzero scalar multiple of the series is also summable and vice versa: if a series is divergent, then any nonzero scalar multiple of it is also divergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Scalar multiplication of real numbers and complex numbers is associative, commutative, invertible, and it distributes over series addition.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In summary, series addition and scalar multiplication gives the set of convergent series and the set of series of real numbers the structure of a real vector space.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Similarly, one gets complex vector spaces for series and convergent series of complex numbers.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] All these vector spaces are infinite dimensional.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Series multiplication of absolutely convergent series of real numbers and complex numbers is associative, commutative, and distributes over series addition.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] One of the simplest tests for convergence of a series, applicable to all series, is the *vanishing condition* or *⁠ n ⁠th-term test*: If ${\textstyle \lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}\neq 0}$ , then the series diverges; if ${\textstyle \lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}=0}$ , then the test is inconclusive.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When every term of a series is a non-negative real number, for instance when the terms are the absolute values of another series of real numbers or complex numbers, the sequence of partial sums is non-decreasing.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Therefore a series with non-negative terms converges if and only if the sequence of partial sums is bounded, and so finding a bound for a series or for the absolute values of its terms is an effective way to prove convergence or absolute convergence of a series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The exact value of this series is ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{6}}\pi ^{2}}$ ; see Basel problem.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] This type of bounding strategy is the basis for general series comparison tests.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Using comparisons to geometric series specifically, those two general comparison tests imply two further common and generally useful tests for convergence of series with non-negative terms or for absolute convergence of series with general terms.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] First is the *ratio test*: if there exists a constant $C<1$ such that $\left\vert {\tfrac {a_{n+1}}{a_{n}}}\right\vert <C$ for all sufficiently large n , then ${\textstyle \sum a_{n}}$ converges absolutely.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When the ratio is less than 1 , but not less than a constant less than 1 , convergence is possible but this test does not establish it.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Second is the *root test*: if there exists a constant $C<1$ such that $\textstyle \left\vert a_{n}\right\vert ^{1/n}\leq C$ for all sufficiently large n , then ${\textstyle \sum a_{n}}$ converges absolutely.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Using comparisons to flattened-out versions of a series leads to Cauchy's condensation test: if the sequence of terms $a_{n}$ is non-negative and non-increasing, then the two series ${\textstyle \sum a_{n}}$ and ${\textstyle \sum 2^{k}a_{(2^{k})}}$ are either both convergent or both divergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] A series of real or complex numbers is said to be *conditionally convergent* (or *semi-convergent*) if it is convergent but not absolutely convergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Conditional convergence is tested for differently than absolute convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] One important example of a test for conditional convergence is the *alternating series test* or *Leibniz test*: A series of the form ${\textstyle \sum (-1)^{n}a_{n}}$ with all $a_{n}>0$ is called *alternating*.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Such a series converges if the non-negative sequence $a_{n}$ is monotone decreasing and converges to 0 .
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Taking $\lambda _{n}=(-1)^{n}$ recovers the alternating series test.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Other specialized convergence tests for specific types of series include the Dini test for Fourier series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The evaluation of truncation errors of series is important in numerical analysis (especially validated numerics and computer-assisted proof).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] It can be used to prove convergence and to analyze rates of convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When conditions of the alternating series test are satisfied by ${\textstyle S:=\sum _{m=0}^{\infty }(-1)^{m}u_{m}}$ , there is an exact error evaluation.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] By using the ratio, we can obtain the evaluation of the error term when the hypergeometric series is truncated.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Under many circumstances, it is desirable to assign generalized sums to series which fail to converge in the strict sense that their sequences of partial sums do not converge.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] A *summation method* is any method for assigning sums to divergent series in a way that systematically extends the classical notion of the sum of a series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Summation methods include Cesàro summation, generalized Cesàro ⁠ $(C,\alpha )$ ⁠ summation, Abel summation, and Borel summation, in order of applicability to increasingly divergent series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] These methods are all based on sequence transformations of the original series of terms or of its sequence of partial sums.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] A variety of general results concerning possible summability methods are known.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The Silverman–Toeplitz theorem characterizes *matrix summation methods*, which are methods for summing a divergent series by applying an infinite matrix to the vector of coefficients.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The most general methods for summing a divergent series are non-constructive and concern Banach limits.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] is pointwise convergent to a limit ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ on a set ⁠ E ⁠ if the series converges for each ⁠ x ⁠ in ⁠ E ⁠ as a series of real or complex numbers.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] converge to ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ as ⁠ N ⁠ goes to infinity for each ⁠ x ⁠ in ⁠ E ⁠.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] A stronger notion of convergence of a series of functions is uniform convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] converges to zero with increasing ⁠ N ⁠, *independently* of ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Uniform convergence is desirable for a series because many properties of the terms of the series are then retained by the limit.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] For example, if a series of continuous functions converges uniformly, then the limit function is also continuous.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Similarly, if the ⁠ $f_{n}$ ⁠ are integrable on a closed and bounded interval ⁠ I ⁠ and converge uniformly, then the series is also integrable on ⁠ I ⁠ and can be integrated term by term.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Tests for uniform convergence include Weierstrass' M-test, Abel's uniform convergence test, Dini's test, and the Cauchy criterion.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] More sophisticated types of convergence of a series of functions can also be defined.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In measure theory, for instance, a series of functions converges almost everywhere if it converges pointwise except on a set of measure zero.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Other modes of convergence depend on a different metric space structure on the space of functions under consideration.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The Taylor series at a point ⁠ c ⁠ of a function is a power series that, in many cases, converges to the function in a neighborhood of ⁠ c ⁠.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] is the Taylor series of $e^{x}$ at the origin and converges to it for every ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Unless it converges only at ⁠ $x=c$ ⁠, such a series converges on a certain open disc of convergence centered at the point ⁠ c ⁠ in the complex plane, and may also converge at some of the points of the boundary of the disc.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The radius of this disc is known as the radius of convergence, and can in principle be determined from the asymptotics of the coefficients ⁠ $a_{n}$ ⁠.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The convergence is uniform on closed and bounded (that is, compact) subsets of the interior of the disc of convergence: to wit, it is uniformly convergent on compact sets.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Historically, mathematicians such as Leonhard Euler operated liberally with infinite series, even if they were not convergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] When calculus was put on a sound and correct foundation in the nineteenth century, rigorous proofs of the convergence of series were always required.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] While many uses of power series refer to their sums, it is also possible to treat power series as *formal sums*, meaning that no addition operations are actually performed, and the symbol "+" is an abstract symbol of conjunction which is not necessarily interpreted as corresponding to addition.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In this setting, the sequence of coefficients itself is of interest, rather than the convergence of the series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Formal power series are used in combinatorics to describe and study sequences that are otherwise difficult to handle, for example, using the method of generating functions.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The Hilbert–Poincaré series is a formal power series used to study graded algebras.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Even if the limit of the power series is not considered, if the terms support appropriate structure then it is possible to define operations such as addition, multiplication, derivative, antiderivative for power series "formally", treating the symbol "+" as if it corresponded to addition.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In the most common setting, the terms come from a commutative ring, so that the formal power series can be added term-by-term and multiplied via the Cauchy product.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In this case the algebra of formal power series is the total algebra of the monoid of natural numbers over the underlying term ring.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] If the underlying term ring is a differential algebra, then the algebra of formal power series is also a differential algebra, with differentiation performed term-by-term.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Laurent series generalize power series by admitting terms into the series with negative as well as positive exponents.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] If such a series converges, then in general it does so in an annulus rather than a disc, and possibly some boundary points.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The series converges uniformly on compact subsets of the interior of the annulus of convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Like the zeta function, Dirichlet series in general play an important role in analytic number theory.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Generally a Dirichlet series converges if the real part of ⁠ s ⁠ is greater than a number called the abscissa of convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In many cases, a function defined by a Dirichlet series is an analytic function that can be extended outside the domain of convergence of the series by analytic continuation.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] For example, the Dirichlet series for the zeta function converges absolutely when ⁠ $\operatorname {Re} (s)>1$ ⁠, but the zeta function can be extended to a holomorphic function defined on $\mathbb {C} \setminus \{1\}$ with a simple pole at ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] This series can be directly generalized to general Dirichlet series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The most important example of a trigonometric series is the Fourier series of a function.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Asymptotic series, typically called asymptotic expansions, are infinite series whose terms are functions of a sequence of different asymptotic orders and whose partial sums are approximations of some other function in an asymptotic limit.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In general they do not converge, but they are still useful as sequences of approximations, each of which provides a value close to the desired answer for a finite number of terms.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] They are crucial tools in perturbation theory and in the analysis of algorithms.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] An asymptotic series cannot necessarily be made to produce an answer as exactly as desired away from the asymptotic limit, the way that an ordinary convergent series of functions can.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In fact, a typical asymptotic series reaches its best practical approximation away from the asymptotic limit after a finite number of terms; if more terms are included, the series will produce less accurate approximations.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Infinite series play an important role in modern analysis of Ancient Greek philosophy of motion, particularly in Zeno's paradoxes.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Zeno is said to have argued that therefore Achilles could *never* reach the tortoise, and thus that continuous movement must be an illusion.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Zeno divided the race into infinitely many sub-races, each requiring a finite amount of time, so that the total time for Achilles to catch the tortoise is given by a series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The resolution of the purely mathematical and imaginative side of the paradox is that, although the series has an infinite number of terms, it has a finite sum, which gives the time necessary for Achilles to catch up with the tortoise.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Greek mathematician Archimedes produced the first known summation of an infinite series with a method that is still used in the area of calculus today.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] He used the method of exhaustion to calculate the area under the arc of a parabola with the summation of an infinite series, and gave a remarkably accurate approximation of π.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In the 14th century, French mathematician Nicole Oresme developed the first proof of the divergence of the harmonic series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] His work, along with the contemporaneous work of Richard Swineshead on a different series, marked the first appearance of infinite series other than the geometric series in mathematics.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Mathematicians from the Kerala school in medieval India were studying infinite series c.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] One of their most important works—series expansion for trigonometric functions—were described in Sanskrit verse in a book by Neelakanta called *Tantrasangraha* (around 1500), and again in a commentary on this work, called *Tantrasangraha-vakhya*, of unknown authorship.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The theorems were stated without proof, but proofs for the series for sine, cosine, and inverse tangent were provided a century later in the work *Yuktibhasa* (c.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] 1530), written in Malayalam, by Jyesthadeva, and also in a commentary on *Tantrasangraha*.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In the 17th century, James Gregory worked in the new decimal system on infinite series and published several Maclaurin series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] In 1715, a general method for constructing the Taylor series for all functions for which they exist was provided by Brook Taylor.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Leonhard Euler in the 18th century, developed the theory of hypergeometric series and q-series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The investigation of the validity of infinite series is considered to begin with Gauss in the 19th century.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] on which Gauss published a memoir in 1812.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] It established simpler criteria of convergence, and the questions of remainders and the range of convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Cauchy (1821) insisted on strict tests of convergence; he showed that if two series are convergent their product is not necessarily so, and with him begins the discovery of effective criteria.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The terms *convergence* and *divergence* had been introduced long before by Gregory (1668).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Leonhard Euler and Gauss had given various criteria, and Colin Maclaurin had anticipated some of Cauchy's discoveries.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Cauchy advanced the theory of power series by his expansion of a complex function in such a form.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] corrected certain of Cauchy's conclusions, and gave a completely scientific summation of the series for complex values of m and x .
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] He showed the necessity of considering the subject of continuity in questions of convergence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] General criteria began with Kummer (1835), and have been studied by Eisenstein (1847), Weierstrass in his various contributions to the theory of functions, Dini (1867), DuBois-Reymond (1873), and many others.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Pringsheim's memoirs (1889) present the most complete general theory.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The theory of uniform convergence was treated by Cauchy (1821), his limitations being pointed out by Abel, but the first to attack it successfully were Seidel and Stokes (1847–48).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Cauchy took up the problem again (1853), acknowledging Abel's criticism, and reaching the same conclusions which Stokes had already found.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Thomae used the doctrine (1866), but there was great delay in recognizing the importance of distinguishing between uniform and non-uniform convergence, in spite of the demands of the theory of functions.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] A series is said to be semi-convergent (or conditionally convergent) if it is convergent but not absolutely convergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Semi-convergent series were studied by Poisson (1823), who also gave a general form for the remainder of the Maclaurin formula.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] The most important solution of the problem is due, however, to Jacobi (1834), who attacked the question of the remainder from a different standpoint and reached a different formula.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] This expression was also worked out, and another one given, by Malmsten (1847).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Genocchi (1852) has further contributed to the theory.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Among the early writers was Wronski, whose "loi suprême" (1815) was hardly recognized until Cayley (1873) brought it into prominence.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Fourier series were being investigated as the result of physical considerations at the same time that Gauss, Abel, and Cauchy were working out the theory of infinite series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Series for the expansion of sines and cosines, of multiple arcs in powers of the sine and cosine of the arc had been treated by Jacob Bernoulli (1702) and his brother Johann Bernoulli (1701) and still earlier by Vieta.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Euler and Lagrange simplified the subject, as did Poinsot, Schröter, Glaisher, and Kummer.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Fourier (1807) set for himself a different problem, to expand a given function of ⁠ x ⁠ in terms of the sines or cosines of multiples of ⁠ x ⁠, a problem which he embodied in his *Théorie analytique de la chaleur* (1822).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Euler had already given the formulas for determining the coefficients in the series; Fourier was the first to assert and attempt to prove the general theorem.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Poisson (1820–23) also attacked the problem from a different standpoint.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Fourier did not, however, settle the question of convergence of his series, a matter left for Cauchy (1826) to attempt and for Dirichlet (1829) to handle in a thoroughly scientific manner (see convergence of Fourier series).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Dirichlet's treatment (*Crelle*, 1829), of trigonometric series was the subject of criticism and improvement by Riemann (1854), Heine, Lipschitz, Schläfli, and du Bois-Reymond.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p01] Among other prominent contributors to the theory of trigonometric and Fourier series were Dini, Hermite, Halphen, Krause, Byerly and Appell.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] Definitions may be given for infinitary sums over an arbitrary index set $I.$ This generalization introduces two main differences from the usual notion of series: first, there may be no specific order given on the set I ; second, the set I may be uncountable.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] The notions of convergence need to be reconsidered for these, then, because for instance the concept of conditional convergence depends on the ordering of the index set.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] Any sum over non-negative reals can be understood as the integral of a non-negative function with respect to the counting measure, which accounts for the many similarities between the two constructions.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] When the supremum is finite then the set of $i\in I$ such that $a_{i}>0$ is countable.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] $\sum _{i\in I}a_{i}=\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }a_{i_{k}},$ provided the value $\infty$ is allowed for the sum of the series.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] Because $\operatorname {Finite} (I)$ is not totally ordered, this is not a limit of a sequence of partial sums, but rather of a net.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] When X is complete, a family $\left(a_{i}\right)_{i\in I}$ is unconditionally summable in X if and only if the finite sums satisfy the latter Cauchy net condition.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] This need not be true in a general abelian topological group (see examples below).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] By nature, the definition of unconditional summability is insensitive to the order of the summation.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] Conversely, if every permutation of a series $\textstyle \sum a_{n}$ converges, then the series is unconditionally convergent.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] It is called **absolutely summable** if in addition, for every continuous seminorm p on $X,$ the family $\left(p\left(x_{i}\right)\right)_{i\in I}$ is summable.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] If X is a normable space and if $\left(x_{i}\right)_{i\in I}$ is an absolutely summable family in $X,$ then necessarily all but a countable collection of $x_{i}$ ’s are zero.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] Hence, in normed spaces, it is usually only ever necessary to consider series with countably many terms.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] Summable families play an important role in the theory of nuclear spaces.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] The notion of series can be easily extended to the case of a seminormed space.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] More generally, convergence of series can be defined in any abelian Hausdorff topological group.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] in which case all but at most countably many of the values $\left|x_{i}\right|$ are necessarily zero.
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] If a countable series of vectors in a Banach space converges absolutely then it converges unconditionally, but the converse only holds in finite-dimensional Banach spaces (theorem of Dvoretzky & Rogers (1950)).
[src:real-analysis/series-mathematics-p02] If all limits exist up to $\alpha _{0},$ then the series converges.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] In the mathematical field of analysis, **uniform convergence** is a mode of convergence of functions stronger than pointwise convergence.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] A sequence of functions $(f_{n})$ **converges uniformly** to a limiting function f if, roughly speaking, they **uniformly approximate** the function f over the whole domain, meaning that all but finitely many of the functions of the sequence lie in a uniform error bar of the original function.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] Graphically this means that, given any thin band around the graph of f , the graphs of all but finitely many of the functions $f_{n}$ lie within that thin band.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] This is in contrast to pointwise convergence, in which all but finitely many of the functions lie in a thin band at each point, but the finite set of functions which must be excluded in order for that to be the case varies from point to point.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] The strength of uniform convergence makes it ideal in many applications, where pointwise convergence is not sufficient.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] For example, the uniform limit of a sequence of continuous functions is automatically continuous; the uniform limit of Riemann integrable functions is automatically Riemann integrable.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] With additional hypotheses, differentiability can be transferred to the limit function as well.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] The difference between uniform convergence and pointwise convergence was not fully appreciated early in the history of calculus, leading to instances of faulty reasoning.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] The concept was first formalized by Karl Weierstrass.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] In 1821 Augustin-Louis Cauchy published a proof that a convergent sum of continuous functions is always continuous, to which Niels Henrik Abel in 1826 found purported counterexamples in the context of Fourier series, arguing that Cauchy's proof had to be incorrect.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] Completely standard notions of convergence did not exist at the time, and Cauchy handled convergence using infinitesimal methods.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] When put into the modern language, what Cauchy proved is that a uniformly convergent sequence of continuous functions has a continuous limit.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] The failure of a merely pointwise-convergent limit of continuous functions to converge to a continuous function illustrates the importance of distinguishing between different types of convergence when handling sequences of functions.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] Later Gudermann's pupil, Karl Weierstrass, who attended his course on elliptic functions in 1839–1840, coined the term *gleichmäßig konvergent* (German: *uniformly convergent*) which he used in his 1841 paper *Zur Theorie der Potenzreihen*, published in 1894.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] Independently, similar concepts were articulated by Philipp Ludwig von Seidel and George Gabriel Stokes.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] Under the influence of Weierstrass and Bernhard Riemann this concept and related questions were intensely studied at the end of the 19th century by Hermann Hankel, Paul du Bois-Reymond, Ulisse Dini, Cesare Arzelà and others.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] We first define uniform convergence for real-valued functions, although the concept is readily generalized to functions mapping to metric spaces and, more generally, uniform spaces (see below).
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] Suppose E is a set and $(f_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ is a sequence of real-valued functions defined on it.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] to indicate that convergence is uniform.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] then $f_{n}$ converges to f uniformly if and only if $d_{n}\to 0$ as $n\to \infty$ .
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] The sequence $(f_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ is said to be **locally uniformly convergent** with limit f if E is a metric space and for every $x\in E$ , there exists an $r>0$ such that $(f_{n})$ converges uniformly on $B(x,r)\cap E$ where $B(x,r)$ is a ball centered at *x* with the radius *r*.
[src:real-analysis/uniform-convergence] It is clear that uniform convergence implies local uniform convergence, which implies pointwise convergence.
